prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Sirius A: Band 7
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 7 continuum observations of Sirius A to constrain intrinsic stellar emission at this wavelength.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Only continuum is required to meet the science goal.

The object is a point source and is not expected to be confused/contaminated by other objects. As such, we request 1" resolution and further request that the same array configuration be used here as will be done for the band 4 and 6 observations of Sirius A and the band 6 and 7 observations of Gam Lep. This point is important for the absolute flux calibration to ensure there is as little delay as possible between the observations in different bands. Because the objects are point sources, extended emission is not a consideration.

We require continuum observations of Sirius A in band 7 to measure the intrinsic emission from the star at this wavelength. The requested sensitivity gives an S/N of about 100. This yields a measurement that is similar in precision to bands 4 and 6 for Sirius A. Because this observation is heavily overhead-limited, the additional sensitivity (compared with say an S/N of 10) is very small in total time and requires about 2 min on source (according to the OT). The science case for having a higher S/N for Sirius A is that it will ensure that uncertainty in the measurement is determined by only the flux calibration and stellar atmosphere intrinsics. Such high-precision measurements will allow follow up studies of Sirius A to monitor variability in, e.g., the chromosphere.
To better manage overhead, we request to execute the Sirius A and Gam Lep observations together (note that they cannot be placed under the same science goal due to their separation, a limitation of the OT).
Considerations regarding absolute flux calibration are discussed below.

The project requires the most well-constrained absolute flux calibration possible (as demonstrated for HL Tau [21]) if the results are to be used by the debris community and stellar atmosphere modellers, particularly with only three targets (four stars) at this time. We have been in communication with contact scientists at ALMA through the helpdesk, and they recommended that this proposal be submitted with user-defined calibration.
The flux and bandpass calibrators are chosen from some of the most frequently monitored quasars. The more stable one is used as the flux calibrator and the stronger one as the bandpass calibrator. The phase calibrator was chosen to be within 5 degrees and suitable up to band 7.
The calibrators are: Flux/Amplitude J0538-4405 Bandpass J0522-364 Phase J0609-1542
We further request that the Sirius A and Gam Lep observations be executed together.
The user-defined calibration will be re-examined in communication with the contact scientist should this observing plan be executed.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Sirius A: Band 4
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 4 continuum observations of Sirius A to detect intrinsic stellar emission.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Only continuum is required to meet the science goal.

Sirius A is a point source and is not expected to be confused/contaminated by other objects, such as Sirius B. As such, we request 2."3 resolution and further request that the same array configuration be used as here as will be done for the band 6 and 7 observations of Sirius A and Gam Lep. This point is important for the absolute flux calibration to ensure there is as little delay as possible between the observations in different bands. Because the objects are point sources, extended emission is not a consideration.

We require continuum observations of Sirius A in band 4 to measure the intrinsic emission from the star at this wavelength. The requested sensitivity gives an S/N of about 100. This yields a measurement that is similar in precision to the higher frequency bands. Because this observation is heavily overhead-limited, the additional sensitivity (compared with say an S/N of 10) is very small in total time and requires about 7 min on source (according to the OT). The science case for having a higher S/N for Sirius A is that it will ensure that uncertainty in the measurement is determined by only the flux calibration and stellar atmosphere intrinsics. Such high-precision measurements will allow follow up studies of Sirius A to monitor variability in, e.g., the chromosphere, which may be particularly important in band 4 (see Fig. 1 and 2, as well as [13]).
The purpose of the band 4 observations is specifically to feed into stellar atmosphere models.
Considerations regarding absolute flux calibration are discussed below.

The project requires the most well-constrained absolute flux calibration possible (as demonstrated for HL Tau [21]) if the results are to be used by the debris community and stellar atmosphere modellers, particularly with only three targets (four stars) at this time. We have been in communication with contact scientists at ALMA through the helpdesk, and they recommended that this proposal be submitted with user-defined calibration.
The flux and bandpass calibrators are chosen from some of the most frequently monitored quasars. The more stable one is used as the flux calibrator and the stronger one as the bandpass calibrator. The phase calibrator was chosen to be within 5 degrees and suitable up to band 7.
The calibrators are: Flux/Amplitude J0538-4405 Bandpass J0522-364 Phase J0609-1542
We further request that the Sirius A band 4 observations be executed within a similar time frame to the Sirius A and Gam Lep band 6 and 7 observations.
The user-defined calibration will be re-examined in communication with the contact scientist should this observing plan be executed.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Gam Vir: Band 7
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 7 observations of Gam Vir A and B to measure intrinsic stellar emission at this wavelength.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Only continuum is required to meet the science goal.

The binary components are expected to be separated by > 1."8 by the earliest possible observation [20]. As such, we request 500 mas to ensure that the binary is resolved and such that the observations can be taken concurrently (same array configuration) with the band 6 observations. This point is important for the absolute flux calibration to ensure there is as little delay as possible between the observations in different bands. Because the objects are point sources, extended emission is not a consideration.

We require continuum observations of Gam Vir A and B in band 7 to measure the intrinsic emission from the stars at this wavelength. The stars are identical (giving added value to the target), and they will be resolved by the observations.
The requested sensitivity gives an S/N of about 12. This is slightly higher than that requested for Gam Lep. The reason is that Gam Lep's flux density is extrapolated from 100 um Herschel measurements [25]. Such observations are expected to already be in the brightness temperature minimum, and are thus unlikely to underpredict the flux density. In contrast, the flux densities for Gam Vir A and B are based on literature values that are more closely tied to the optical properties of the star, which could overestimate the flux density. While there is a reported flux density for Gam Vir A at 100 um [27], it is larger than that expected for the simple black body noted above. Furthermore, the reported flux density in [27] is about 10 mJy larger for Gam Lep than that reported in [26] (who do not include Gam Vir A or B in their sample). As such, we take the more conservative estimate and further desire a slightly higher S/N to guard against a potential drop of about 20% in brightness temperature at the noted wavelength (as seen in some stellar models).
Considerations regarding absolute flux calibration are discussed below.

The project requires the most well-constrained absolute flux calibration possible (as demonstrated for HL Tau [21]) if the results are to be used by the debris community and stellar atmosphere modellers, particularly with only three targets four stars) at this time. We have been in communication with contact scientists at ALMA through the helpdesk, and they recommended that this proposal be submitted with user-defined calibration.
The flux and bandpass calibrators are chosen from some of the most frequently monitored quasars. The more stable one is used as the flux calibrator and the stronger one as the bandpass calibrator. The phase calibrator was chosen to be within 5 degrees and suitable up to band 7.
The calibrators are: Flux/Amplitude J1337-129 Bandpass J1256-057 Phase J1229+0203
The user-defined calibration will be re-examined in communication with the contact scientist should this observing plan be executed.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Gam Lep: Band 7
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Band 7 continuum observations Gam Lep to constrain intrinsic stellar emission at this wavelength.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Only continuum is required to meet the science goal.

The object is a point source and is not expected to be confused/contaminated by other objects. As such, we request 1" resolution and further request that the same array configuration be used here as will be done for the band 4, 6, and 7 observations of Sirius A and the band 6 observation of Gam Lep. This point is important for the absolute flux calibration to ensure there is as little delay as possible between the observations in different bands. Because the objects are point sources, extended emission is not a consideration.

We require continuum observations of Gam Lep in band 7 to measure the intrinsic emission from this star at 870 um. To better manage overhead, we request to execute the Sirius A and Gam Lep observations together (note that they cannot be placed under the same science goal due to their separation, a limitation of the OT). The sensivity limit is based on an extrapolated black body for Gam Lep from 100 um to 870 um using the DEBRIS results [26] and requesting a minimum S/N of 10. The DEBRIS survey is measuring stellar flux in regions where there is an expected brightness temperature minimum (Fig 1 and 2). As a result, the actual S/N may be better at 870 um. A S/N of 10 or greater is needed to ensure that we have a reliable measurement of the intrinsic flux of the star.
Absolute flux calibration considerations are discussed below.

The calibrators are: Flux/Amplitude J0538-4405 Bandpass J0522-364 Phase J0609-1542

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to test stellar atmosphere models at submillimetre/millmetre (submm/mm) wavelengths by observing Sirius A in bands 4, 6, and 7, as well as Gam Lep and Gam Vir in bands 6 and 7. Brightness temperatures can deviate significantly from extrapolated black bodies at these wavelengths due to, e.g., chromosphere effects. However, there is a paucity of stellar emission data in the submm/mm. Determining the origins of stellar excesses (e.g., excess due to intrinsic stellar properties or due to dust at small stellar separations) can only be done by properly calibrating stellar models to match submm/mm fluxes. The proposed work is a crucial step in searching for exo-asteroid belts and other debris. Furthermore, the results have implications for interpreting future and existing hot stellar excess data, as well as informing target selections for future studies.
